+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01NMEarH8p1MxXVULPaCv5g8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand. The `2024-01-31` invoice date: `new Date('2024-01-31T00:00:00Z')` in `America/New_York` timezone gives January 30 19:00 local time. `getMonth()` returns 0 (January), so `month = 1`. That's actually correct for January 31st.\n\nBut wait — the test expects Jan to have 3 invoices (10th, 25th, 31st) but gets 4. Where does the 4th come from? The Feb 1st invoice (`2024-02-01T00:00:00Z`) in New York is Jan 31 19:00, so `getMonth()` returns 0 → month 1 (January)! The Feb 1st invoice is being classified as January due to the timezone issue.\n\nSo the fix is: use `getUTCMonth()` instead of `getMonth()` in `reporting.ts:28`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1158,"cache_read_input_tokens":29532,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1158},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"43e7b3ac-2550-40bb-bae4-b5543685cdbe","uuid":"66683bcd-35c3-4b48-ab86-91f08ef94205"}
